The networking mental model.

When a container starts on a normal, non-host, network, the kernel gives it a network namespace of its own. It's the module-one isolation primitive, applied to networking. That namespace has its own set of interfaces, usually just loopback and a virtual eth-zero; its own eye-pee address or addresses; its own routing table; its own i-p-tables firewall rules; and its own set of open ports.

From inside the container, this looks like a tiny, isolated machine on a network. From the host's point of view, the container's eth-zero is one end of a virtual ethernet pair, called a v-eth pair. The other end plugs into a Linux bridge: docker-zero for the default network, or a b-r bridge for a user-defined one.

So picture container A, with its eth-zero at some address, connected by a v-eth pair into the docker-zero bridge on the host, and the host in turn does network address translation out to its real interface and onto the wider network.

Two consequences explain almost everything that follows. First, containers on the same bridge talk to each other directly, on their container ports; the bridge is essentially a virtual switch between them. That's exactly why two containers on the same network need no dash p between them. Second, outbound traffic is network-address-translated through the host's real interface, so a container can reach the internet. But inbound traffic is blocked by default, because the bridge is private. Getting traffic in requires publishing a port, which is section seven. Everything in this module is a variation on this one picture: namespaces on a bridge, translation on the way out, and publishing to let traffic in.
